ved as investigations into the status of persons and the nature and parameters of social life. No longer conceivable as divine trial or punishment, pain in the nineteenth century came to seem instead like a historical accident suggesting little or nothing about the individual who suffers.A landmark study of Victorian literature and the history of pain, Victorian Pain shows how these writers came to see pain as a social as well as a personal problem. Rather than simply self-evident to the sufferer and unknowable to anyone else, pain was also understood to be produced between persons-and even, perhaps, by the fictions they read.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHuman body in literature. 0aLiterature and sciencezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPain in literature. 0aPainzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054332240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400885176zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400885176.jpg  a978-3-11-054332-2  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN